# Database migrations

When creating or editing migrations in this project:

- Prefer backwards-compatible changes so the currently deployed app keeps working until the new frontend is live.
- Safe patterns: add nullable columns, add new tables/RPCs, add indexes, widen types.
- Avoid breaking changes in a single step — don't drop/rename columns or change RPC signatures without a two-phase migration.
- Order of operations:
  - **Adding** schema/features: run migration first, then deploy frontend that uses it.
  - **Removing** schema/features: deploy frontend that no longer uses it first, then run cleanup migration.
- Local dev and GitHub Pages share the same Supabase project unless env vars say otherwise — migrations affect production immediately.
- Migrations are applied manually (SQL Editor / Supabase CLI), not by the GitHub Pages deploy workflow.

## Examples

```sql
-- ✅ GOOD: add nullable column; old app ignores it, new app can use it
alter table public.picks add column notes text;

-- ✅ GOOD: add new RPC; old app never calls it
create or replace function public.create_league(...) ...

-- ❌ BAD: rename column in one step — breaks deployed app until frontend ships
alter table public.leagues rename column name to display_name;

-- ✅ GOOD: two-phase rename
-- Phase 1: add new column, backfill, keep old column
-- Phase 2 (after deploy): drop old column
```
